{
  "text": "where P r is received power and P n is noise power integrated over the frequency range that corresponds to the velocity measurement range of the lidar Ϯ26 m s Ϫ1 . We define P n as the mean signal power in the absence of atmospheric return (often referred to as the background level with telescope open) and P r ϰ (I 2 ϩ Q 2 ) Ϫ P n . Figure 15 shows the mean SNR profiles (in decibels) for the lidar and profiler during the comparison period on 9 May 1994. Figure 16 contains the mean vertical velocity energy spectra, coherence, and phase angle (e.g., [CITATION_1] for the lidar and profiler data shown in Fig. 13 . These results were achieved by computing the cross-spectra of the two time series at each of the nine vertical levels. The cross-spectra are then averaged over three Fourier modes and all nine levels to increase the significance of the results.",
